    *The missing arrows.*
    â€˜sinâ€™ and â€˜cosâ€™ only constitute two out
    of six ratios that exist among the sides
    of a right triangle. The four â€œmissing ratiosâ€
    are hereby drawn:

    |> Image
        src=images/svg_ch5_ch_missing_arrows_veiled.svg

    In fact, there is a dedicated, named function
    that computes each of the six ratios. We shall
    now reveal the names of the four missing
    functions (!!):

    |> Image
        src=images/svg_ch5_ch_missing_arrows_unveiled.svg

    Here
    â€œsecâ€ is short for _secant_,
    â€œtanâ€ is short for _tangent_,
    â€œcotâ€ is short for _cotangent_, and
    â€œcscâ€ is short for _cosecant_.

    To be clear, multiplying by

    $$
    \sec(\theta)
    $$

    takes you from â€˜adjacentâ€™ to â€˜hypotenuseâ€™, multiplying by

    $$
    \csc(\theta)
    $$

    takes you from â€˜oppositeâ€™ to â€˜hypotenuseâ€™, multiplying by

    $$
    \tan(\theta)
    $$

    takes you from â€˜adjacentâ€™ to â€˜oppositeâ€™,
    and multiplying by

    $$
    \cot(\theta)
    $$

    takes you from â€˜oppositeâ€™ to â€˜adjacentâ€™. (!)

    You may observe that

    $$
    \sec = {1\over \cos}
    $$
    and that
    $$
    \csc = {1\over \sin}
    $$

    as multiplying by â€˜cosâ€™ undoes the work
    of multiplying by â€˜secâ€™, and likewise for
    â€˜sinâ€™ and â€˜cscâ€™; also,

    $$
    \,\tan = {1\over \cot},
    $$
    $$
    \cot = {1\over \tan}
    $$

    modulo a very small technicality (to do
    with the fact that ${1\over \infty} \ne 0$,
    or to do with the fact that
    what people think of as â€œ$\pm\infty$â€
    is, in fact, an _undefined_ value of the function),
    and

    $$
    \tan \,=\, \sec \cdot \sin \,\,=\,\, {\sin\!\!\!\!\phantom{1}\over \cos}
    $$
    $$
    \cot \,=\, \csc \cdot \cos \,\,=\,\, {\cos\!\!\!\!\phantom{1}\over \sin}
    $$

    since one way to reach â€˜oppositeâ€™ from
    â€˜adjacentâ€™ is to go via â€˜hypotenuseâ€™, and
    vice-versa for reaching â€˜adjacentâ€™ from
    â€˜oppositeâ€™. (In fact, the next-to-last
    identity played a role in our proof of the
    Gregorinovich sandwich.) (Indeed,

    $$
    %\sin(\theta) < \theta < \tan(\theta)\rt{0.1}
    \sin(\theta) < \theta < \tan(\theta)\rt{0.1}
    $$

    !! ...in this form, as well!)
    is another way of writing the Grigorinovich
    sandwich.)

